# lib-purity.skill

## Meta
pkg: archkit (internal convention)
docs: src/lib/, SYSTEM.md
updated: 2026-06-06

## Use
src/lib/ holds PURE libraries — parsers, generators, detectors, goal/test helpers.
They take inputs and return data. Side effects (fs writes, process.exit, console output,
process.env mutation, network) live in src/commands/ and bin/. This split is what lets
the MCP layer and the CLI reuse the same library code without surprises.

## Patterns
- A lib function receives `archDir`/`cwd`/content as arguments — it does not call
  findArchDir() or read process.argv itself.
- Parsers (parsers.mjs) return plain objects; callers decide what to print.
- package.json `version` and .claude-plugin/plugin.json `version` ship as ONE unit —
  bump both together (scripts/check-version-sync.mjs enforces this on prepublish).

## Gotchas
WRONG: export function parseIndex(){ const c = fs.readFileSync(findArchDir()+"/INDEX.md"); ... }
RIGHT: export function parseIndex(content){ ... }  // caller does the fs read + passes content in
WHY: pure parsers are reused by warmup, drift, doctor, and the MCP tools; baking in fs/path lookups couples them to one call site and breaks tests that feed fixture strings.

WRONG: bump package.json to 1.9.1 and ship
RIGHT: bump BOTH package.json and .claude-plugin/plugin.json to 1.9.1 in the same commit
WHY: the two version fields ship as one unit; check-version-sync.mjs fails prepublish if they drift, and the marketplace serves a mismatched plugin.

WRONG: console.log(...) or process.exit(1) inside a src/lib/ helper
RIGHT: return a result/throw archkitError; let the command module in src/commands/ print and exit
WHY: libs run inside the MCP server too — stdout corrupts JSON-RPC and process.exit() kills the server.

## Boundaries
src/lib/ does NOT import from src/commands/ or bin/ (one-way dependency: commands → lib).
If a lib needs orchestration, that orchestration belongs in the command, not the lib.

## Snippets
```js
// src/commands/resolve/warmup.mjs — command does I/O, lib stays pure
const systemContent = loadFile(archDir, "SYSTEM.md"); // command-side read
const system = parseSystem(systemContent);            // pure lib, string in
```
